 insight into the larger patterns that place Black women at such high risk on a national level. She shows how Black mothers communicate with their daughters about health, sexuality, and intimacy, including how they attempt to promote healthy living standards even as they navigate widespread, systemic challenges. Ultimately, Berger highlights the important role that family—and specifically, the relationship between mothers and daughters—plays in improving public health outcomes. Black Women’s Health takes a much-needed, intimate look at how Black women and girls navigate different paths to wellness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  a.  aAfrican American daughters.  aAfrican American mothers.  aAfrican-American women.  aBlack feminism.  aBlack girls.  aCommunication.  aDaughters.  aDiet.  aFocus groups.  aGatekeepers.  aGender and media.  aGendered peer pressure.  aGendered scripts.  aGood girl and bad girl culture.  aHIV/AIDS.  aHealth providers.  aHealth.  aInheritances.  aIntersectionality.  aIntimacy.  aMixed messages.  aNarratives.  aNorth Carolina.  aPleasure.  aPregnancy.  aPublic policy.  aRacial and gender health disparities.  aResponsibility.  aSTDS.  aSexual education.  aSexual health.  aThe South.  aTrust.  aTypology.  aWell-being.  abarriers.  acleanliness.  adiet.  aexercise.  agrandmothers.  ahealth care access.  ahealth disparities.  ahealth.  amothers.  apressure.  arespect.  asexuality.  atrust.  avirginity.  aworldviews.  ayoung women.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479876587.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479876587423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479876587/original  aEBA_BACKALL